# LAMMPS Input File
# Licensed under CC BY 4.0
# A Set of Materials-Science Tutorials for the LAMMPS Simulation Package: 2. Materials Science
# By Simon Gravelle, Mark A. Tschopp, Jacob R. Gissinger, and Axel Kohlmeyer
# Tutorial 3: 1. Vacancy formation energy
#
# Build a perfect fcc aluminum supercell at the equilibrium lattice constant
# of the Zhou EAM potential (from Tutorial 1), record its energy, remove the
# atom closest to the box center, relax the remaining atoms, and evaluate the
# vacancy formation energy from the energy balance
#     Ef(vac) = E(N-1) - (N-1)/N * E(N)
# The supercell size is an index variable, so the size convergence can be
# checked from the Set Variables dialog or the command line, e.g.
#     lmp -in vacancy.lmp -var ncell 4

# 1) Initialization
units metal
dimension 3
boundary p p p
atom_style atomic

# 2) System definition
variable ncell index 3           # half the supercell size in conventional fcc cells
variable a0 index 4.08165        # Zhou EAM equilibrium value from Tutorial 1
lattice fcc ${a0} origin 0.25 0.25 0.25
region box block -${ncell} ${ncell} -${ncell} ${ncell} -${ncell} ${ncell}
create_box 1 box
create_atoms 1 box

# 3) Settings
pair_style eam/alloy
pair_coeff * * Al_zhou.eam.alloy Al

# 4) Monitoring
thermo 10
thermo_style custom step pe press fnorm

# 5) Reference energy of the perfect crystal
fix move all nve
run 0 post no
variable natoms0 equal $(count(all))
variable epe0    equal $(pe)

# 6) Create the vacancy: delete a random atom near the box center
region vac sphere 0.25 0.25 0.25 ${a0} units box
delete_atoms random count 1 no all vac 131212345
print "Deleted $(v_natoms0-count(all)) atom(s)"

# 7) Relax the atomic positions at fixed box size
min_style cg
minimize 1.0e-10 1.0e-12 10000 100000

# 8) Formation energy from the energy balance
variable efvac equal pe-(v_natoms0-1)/v_natoms0*v_epe0
print "--------------------------------------------"
print "Atoms in the perfect cell  = ${natoms0}"
print "Vacancy formation energy   = $(v_efvac:%.4f) eV"
print "--------------------------------------------"
